316-1 Simulation Exercise
\end_layout

\end_inset

316-1 Simulation Exercise: Monte Carlo Simulation of Decomposition in a
 Binary Alloy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Scientific problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to analyze the thermodynamic evolution of a A-B alloy by simulation.
 We assume that this system has the phase diagram presented in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:A-B-alloy-phase"

\end_inset

.
 In this figure we see that for temperatures lower than 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{C}$
\end_inset

, the A-B alloy decomposes in two phases 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 with equilibrium concentrations 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 The experiment that we want to model involves the following steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We mix together the same number of moles of elements A and B to obtain a
 homogeneous alloy at some temperature above 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The temperature is reduced to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The temperature is held fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

, and the system evolves to form two different phases, with compositions
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/diagphi.svg
	width 40text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:A-B-alloy-phase"

\end_inset

A-B alloy phase diagram
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Atomistic Monte Carlo Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we introduce the Atomistic Monte Carlo model that we will
 use to model the decomposition of the A-B alloy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Atomistic model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Atomistic-model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model, we suppose that the two elements (A and B) have the same
 lattice structure.
 This lattice is represented by a matrix with periodic boundary conditions
 on its edges (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Lattice-with-periodic"

\end_inset

).
 In 2 dimensions the left edge is connected to the right edge and the upper
 edge is connected to the lower edge.
 We reproduce the system evolution at the atomistic level: vacancies present
 in the lattice migrate from site to site by exchanging their position with
 their first nearest neighbors.
 The successive displacements of vacancies make the system evolve toward
 its equilibrium state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/periodic_boundary.png
	width 40text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Lattice-with-periodic"

\end_inset

Lattice with periodic boundary conditions.
 The blue and red dashed lines represent bonds between sites induced by
 periodic boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Monte Carlo model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The thermodynamic evolution of the alloy is modeled with a Monte Carlo process.
 The principle of Monte Carlo simulations is to model the A-B alloy evolution
 in a statistic way.
 To understand this model we can consider individual jumps of a vacancy
 into one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 nearest neighbor positions.
 Within a certain specified time step, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

, these different possible jumps occur with a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is an index that indicates which direction the vacancy will move.
 In a simple cubic lattice, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 = 6, and the 6 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 correspond to jumps in the positive and negative x, y and z directions.
 The sum over all possible jump probabilities in the statistical time must
 sum to 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\displaystyle \sum_{\mu=1}^{z}}\varGamma_{\mu}=1\label{eq:proba-event}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To figure out which direction the vacancy moves, we draw a random number
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 between 0 and 1.
 The jump performed by the system during the time 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 one such that the following condition holds: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\displaystyle \sum_{\mu=1}^{k-1}\varGamma_{\mu}}<r_{n}\leq{\displaystyle \sum_{\mu=1}^{k}\varGamma_{\mu}}\label{eq:choice}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Probabilities of transitions 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are related to the energetic barrier associated with vacancy motion, which
 we refer to as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E_{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 Because vacancy hopping is a thermally activated process, we can use an
 Arrhenius rate expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma_{\mu}=\varGamma_{0}\exp\left(-\frac{\Delta E_{\mu}}{k_{B}T_{0}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

 is Boltzmann's constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the temperature of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The energy barrier is the difference between the maximum energy of the system
 during the jump (the position of the migrating atom at this maximum energy
 is called the saddle point) and the energy of the system before the jump.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta E_{\mu}=E^{SP}-E^{ini}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here the superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $SP$
\end_inset

 refers to 'Saddle Point' and 
\begin_inset Formula $ini$
\end_inset

 means 'initial', as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Migration-barrier"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Migration_barrier.jpg
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Migration-barrier"

\end_inset

Schematic representation of the evolution of the system energy during a
 single atomic jump.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Energetic model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "par:Energetic-model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compute the energy barriers of the different possible jumps 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E_{\mu}$
\end_inset

, we have to use an energetic model.
 In Monte Carlo simulations, we usually use an Ising model or Broken bond
 model.
 In this energetic model, we assume that the total energy of the system
 is equal to the sum of interaction energies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{ij}$
\end_inset

 between the different elements (atoms of type A and B and vacancies V)
 placed on the lattice sites.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{\nu}={\displaystyle \varSigma_{ij}\varepsilon_{ij}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this energetic model, the migration barrier of an exchange between
 an element 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and the vacancy 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta E_{\nu}={\displaystyle \sum_{k}}\varepsilon_{Xk}^{SP}-{\displaystyle \sum_{i}}\varepsilon_{Xi}-{\displaystyle \sum_{j}}\varepsilon_{Vj}\label{eq:Emigeps}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{Ak}^{SP}$
\end_inset

 are interaction energies between the atom migrating and its neighbors at
 the saddle point, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{Ai}$
\end_inset

 are interaction energies between the atom migrating and its neighbors before
 the jump and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{Vj}$
\end_inset

 are interaction energies between the vacancy and its neighbors before the
 jump.
 The indices i, j and k indicate the following neighbors:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="4" columns="2">
<features rotate="0" tabularvalignment="middle">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Index
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Meaning
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
i
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
nearest neighbors of the migrating atom before the jump
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
j
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
nearest neighbors of the vacancy before the jump
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
k
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
nearest neighbors of migrating atom at the saddle point
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In theory, the range of interaction distances between elements are unlimited.
 In practice, we usually restrict these interactions to first and sometimes
 second nearest neighbors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Example1.png
	scale 90

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Example1"

\end_inset

Example of configuration of atoms in the lattice.
 The red circles are A atoms and the blue circles are B atoms.
 The square is the vacancy
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the system presented in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Example1"

\end_inset

 has:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
3 A-V interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
1 B-V interaction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
3 A-B interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
9 A-A interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
12 B-B interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\nu}=3\varepsilon_{AV}+1\varepsilon_{BV}+3\varepsilon_{AB}+9\varepsilon_{AA}+12\varepsilon_{BB}$
\end_inset

.
 If we suppose that the vacancy exchange its position with the B atom on
 its left side, the configuration of the system at the saddle point is the
 one presented in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Example2"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Example2.png
	scale 90

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Example2"

\end_inset

Configuration of the system at the saddle point if the vacancy echange its
 position with the B atom on its left
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this configuration, the system has:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2 B-B interactions at the saddle point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2 A-B ineractions at the saddle point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
3 A-B interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
9 A-A interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
9 B-B interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{SP}=2\varepsilon_{BB}^{SP}+2\varepsilon_{BA}^{SP}+3\varepsilon_{AB}+9\varepsilon_{AA}+9\varepsilon_{BB}$
\end_inset

.
 The migration barrier of this jump is therefore: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta E_{\nu}=2\varepsilon_{BB}^{SP}+2\varepsilon_{BA}^{SP}-3\varepsilon_{AV}-1\varepsilon_{BV}-3\varepsilon_{BB}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Modeling of scientific problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Modeling-of-scientific"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we assume that the two elements A and B have the same simple cubic
 lattice.
 We model the A-B alloy as a matrix in 2D with 
\begin_inset Formula $nx$
\end_inset

 rows and 
\begin_inset Formula $ny$
\end_inset

 columns and with periodic boundary conditions on its edges.
 To simplify the problem, we introduce only one vacancy in the lattice (so
 1 vacancy for 
\begin_inset Formula $nx\times ny$
\end_inset

 sites), initially located in the middle of the matrix.
 As we only interest ourselves to the thermodynamic evolution of the system
 (and not to its kinetic evolution), we assume that the alloy evolves with
 normalized time steps of 1 until a maximum time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 At each time step, the vacancy exchanges its position with one of its neighbors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simplify the energetic model we suppose that the sum of interaction energies
 between the atom migrating and its neighbors at the saddle point 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \sum_{k}}\varepsilon_{Xk}^{SP}$
\end_inset

 is a constant equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $3\,eV$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, we suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AA}=\varepsilon_{BB}=\varepsilon_{AV}=\varepsilon_{BV}=0\,eV$
\end_inset

.
 The only interaction which can be different from zero is thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AB}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The free enthalpy of the alloy is expressed by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{mix}=\Omega X_{A}X_{B}-T\Delta S_{mix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 the ordering energy of the alloy and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S_{mix}$
\end_inset

 the configurational entropy of mixing of the alloy given by :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta S_{mix}=-k_{B}\left[X_{A}\ln X_{A}+X_{B}\ln X_{B}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a symmetrical miscibility gap, the ordering energy is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Omega=2k_{B}T_{C}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{C}$
\end_inset

 is the critical temperature of the miscibility gap (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{C}=1000\,K$
\end_inset

 in this study).
 In broken bond models with only first nearest neighbors interactions we
 have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Omega=z\left(\epsilon_{AB}-\frac{1}{2}\left(\varepsilon_{AA}+\varepsilon_{BB}\right)\right)\label{eq:Omega}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the number of first nearest neighbors for a given site.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Algorithmic scheme : Translation of problem in algorithm
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Algorithm"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we translate the problem described previously in an algorithm
 scheme.
 As we are modeling an evolution according to time, our code will contain
 an initial state and an incremental loop on time which will start from
 the initial time (
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

) and finish at a final time (
\begin_inset Formula $t_{max}$
\end_inset

).
 During the time loop (for example between time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n+1}$
\end_inset

), the code will repeat the same operations which will make the matrix go
 from the configuration at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 to the one at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 In this code we suggest that the system evolves with the following steps
 in the time loop:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Evolution of time from 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n+1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Computation of jump frequencies of all possible jumps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Drawing of a random number 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 and choice of a jump according to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:choice"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Completion of chosen jump: exchange of position between vacancy and nearest
 neighbor chosen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exercise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Random walks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this first work, we model the evolution of the system if the equilibrium
 configuration of the alloy is an homogenized state.
 As we only interest ourselves to the thermodynamic evolution of the system
 (and not to its kinetic evolution), we assume that the alloy evolves with
 normalized time steps of 1 until a maximum time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 At each time step, the vacancy exchanges its position with one of its neighbors.
 The vacancy can exchange its position with all its first nearest neighbors
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (and only its first nearest neighbors).
 The difference is that in this section we suppose that all exchanges have
 the same jump frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{XV}$
\end_inset

.
 This is called a
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 random walk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Preliminary work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider a vacancy located on the lattice site 
\begin_inset Formula $(xv,yv)$
\end_inset

 as in Figure (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Coordinates"

\end_inset

).

