\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume
We analyze the migration barrier of an exchange between a vacancy V and
 one of its nearest neighbor 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We note 
\begin_inset Formula $NA$
\end_inset

 the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 first nearest neighbors of type A and 
\begin_inset Formula $NB$
\end_inset

 the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 first nearest neighbors of type B.
 How many first nearest neighbors does X have (we do not compt the vacancy)?
 Express equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Emigeps"

\end_inset

) according to 
\begin_inset Formula $NA$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $NB$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{XA}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{XB}$
\end_inset

 (look at the example given in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par:Energetic-model"

\end_inset

 for help).
 Using that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \sum_{k}}\varepsilon_{Xk}^{SP}=3\,eV$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AA}=\varepsilon_{BB}=\varepsilon_{AV}=\varepsilon_{BV}=0\,eV$
\end_inset

, simplify the equation obtained if X is an element A.
 Same question if X is an element B.
 We observe from these calculations that, to compute the migration barrier
 of a jump, we need to know the type of the element of the exchange (so
 the type of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

) and the type of all 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 first nearest neighbors (to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $NA$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $NB$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume
For a given vacancy position, we want to compute the jump frequency of the
 jump 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gamma}(i)$
\end_inset

).
 We note 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 the vacancy neighbor corresponding to this jump.
 We start by computing 
\begin_inset Formula $NA$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $NB$
\end_inset

 (the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 first nearest neighbors of type A and B).
 We note 
\begin_inset Formula $(xn,yn)$
\end_inset

 the position of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(xnk,ynk)$
\end_inset

 the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 first nearest neighbor 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 goes from 1 to 3, the vacancy position is excluded from these nearest neighbors
).
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
xnk\\
ynk
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
xn\\
yn
\end{array}\right)+\mathrm{nveci}(k)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{nveci}(k)$
\end_inset

 is the column 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times3$
\end_inset

 matrix of relative position of 
\begin_inset Formula $(xnk,ynk)$
\end_inset

 compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $(xn,yn)$
\end_inset

.
 Graph 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Position-of-X"

\end_inset

 gives the position of neighbors 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 compared to the vacancy.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
